    <h1>Event Study ‚Äì Microsoft‚Äôs Acquisition of Activision Blizzard</h1>
    <p class="sub"><strong>Tools:</strong> R, Excel ‚Ä¢ <strong>Focus:</strong> t-tests, CAPM, Multifactor model, CAR</p>

    <div class="section">
      <p>Goal: measure the stock market reaction to Microsoft‚Äôs $68.7B acquisition announcement of Activision Blizzard (Jan 18, 2022). Using an estimation window (Jul 1, 2021 ‚Äì Jan 10, 2022) and an event window (Jan 11‚Äì28, 2022), I computed daily returns, ran a two-sample t-test, estimated CAPM and a sector-adjusted multifactor model, and calculated CAR.</p>
      <div>
        <a class="btn" href="../Event%20Study%20-%20Activision.docx" target="_blank">üìÑ View report</a>
        <a class="btn" href="../data/EventStudy_YahooData.csv" target="_blank">üìà View data (CSV)</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
      <img src="../images/eventstudy_car.png" alt="CAR chart">
      <p class="caption">Figure 1. CAR shows a sharp ~+29% jump immediately after the announcement (Day 0).</p>

      <img src="../images/eventstudy_ttest.png" alt="t-test distribution">
      <p class="caption">Figure 2. Two-sample t-test: t = ‚àí2.72 falls in the rejection region (Œ± = 0.05).</p>

      <img src="../images/eventstudy_capm_results.png" alt="CAPM results">
      <p class="caption">Table 2. CAPM regression: significant Œ± and Œ≤ (p ‚âà 0.003, 0.002), R¬≤ ‚âà 0.07.</p>

      <img src="../images/eventstudy_multifactor_results.png" alt="Multifactor results">
      <p class="caption">Table 3. Multifactor regression with sector factor (ESPO) improves fit; ESPO p ‚âà 0.001.</p>
